  "opinion": "As a transgender woman navigating STEM education in Kansas City, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat manifests in the classroom. When I first entered engineering classes, the subtle whispers about 'not being a real engineer' because of my gender made me question my abilities. This isn't just about individual anxiety—it's a systemic issue where the very idea of being 'unlike' the expected STEM identity creates cognitive load. I've noticed how my depression sometimes makes me withdraw, and when I do, my professors miss the signs that I'm struggling with these stereotypes. The problem isn't that I'm 'less capable'—it's that the environment itself is structured to make me feel like I'm failing before I even start. We must address this by creating inclusive spaces where students can be their authentic selves without fear of judgment. For me, this means mentorship programs that explicitly acknowledge gender identity and cultural background. In Buddhist philosophy, we understand that all beings are interconnected, so treating STEM as a monolithic space ignores the rich diversity of thought that exists. I believe schools should implement regular 'stereotype threat audits' to identify and dismantle biases in curriculum and teaching methods. This isn't just about fixing individual students—it's about building a system that values every student's potential. By centering community and respect, we can transform STEM from a place of anxiety into one of belonging.",
